2. CO2 Data Fit with Classical Decomposition

From Lec-22



Linear Trend + Seasonality + sAR

  acf1 <- acf; library(TSA); acf <- acf1
  data(co2)  #- we are using co2 data in TSA package (there's another one in R)

  library(forecast)
  source("http://gozips.uakron.edu/~nmimoto/477/TS_R-90.txt")  

  
  #--- Take Monthly Averages
  X0 <- co2

  Mav1  <- aggregate(c(X0), list(month=cycle(X0)), mean)$x    #- 1yr long Mtly Av
  M.av1 <- ts(Mav1[cycle(X0)], start=start(X0), freq=frequency(X0))    #- Mtly Av
  Ds.X0 <- X0-M.av1                                 #- Subtract from original

  plot(X0, type="o")           # original
  lines(M.av1, col="blue")     # seasonal averages

  Ds.co2 <- Ds.X0      # seasonality removed
  plot(Ds.co2, type="o", main="De-seasonalized CO2")

  #--- Fit line
  Reg1 <- lm(Ds.co2 ~ time(Ds.co2))
  summary(Reg1)

Model for CO2 data

  • \(s=12\) because freq=12 was set in ts object.

  • Took \(\bigtriangledown_{12}\) then checked for sMA(1) paramter and MA(11) parameters.

  • The drift term (mean after the seasonal difference) was significant. With the drift, sMA(1) parameter was too close to 1, indicating that original series has linear trend with WN \(e_t\).

  • With observation \(Y_t\), \[ Y_t \hspace3mm = \hspace3mm L_t + S_t + X_t \] where \(X_t\) was \(ARMA(2,0) \times (1,0)\) \[ X_t = \phi_1 X_{t-1} + \phi_2 X_{t-2} + \Phi_1 X_{t-12} + e_t \]



3. Forecasting CO2 Data with Classical Decomposition

Monthly CO2 levels at NW territories CANADA from Jan 1959 through Dec 1997.

  acf1 <- acf; library(TSA); acf <- acf1
  data(co2)  #- we are using co2 data in TSA package (there's another one in R)

  library(forecast)
  source("http://gozips.uakron.edu/~nmimoto/477/TS_R-90.txt")  

  plot(co2, type="o", main='CO2 Data')

  ## In Lec-22, after taking diff( , 12). sMA(1) coefficient was very close to 1,
  ## indicating Trend + Seasonality + AR(p) + e model

  #--- Take Monthly Averages
  X0 <- co2

  Mav1  <- aggregate(c(X0), list(month=cycle(X0)), mean)$x    #- 1yr long Mtly Av
  M.av1 <- ts(Mav1[cycle(X0)], start=start(X0), freq=frequency(X0))    #- Mtly Av
  Ds.X0 <- X0-M.av1                                 #- Subtract from original

  plot(X0, type="o")           # original
  lines(M.av1, col="blue")     # seasonal averages

  #--- Remove Seasonallity, make it ts obj 
  Ds.co2 <- ts(Ds.X0, start=c(1994,1), freq=12)    # ts obj w seasonality removed
  plot(Ds.co2, type="o", main="De-seasonalized CO2")

  #--- Arima modeling w Linear Trend
  Fit12 <- Arima( Ds.co2, order=c(2,0,0), seasonal=c(2,0,0), xreg=time(Ds.co2))
  Fit12
## Series: Ds.co2 
## Regression with ARIMA(2,0,0)(2,0,0)[12] errors 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1     ar2    sar1    sar2   intercept  time(Ds.co2)
##       0.3855  0.2622  0.2462  0.2003  -3624.1376        1.8126
## s.e.  0.0852  0.0891  0.0901  0.0927    150.3886        0.0752
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.5676:  log likelihood=-148.18
## AIC=310.36   AICc=311.26   BIC=330.54
  #--- 12-step prediction w Sesonal average ---
  Y   <- co2         # Y should be TS object
  Mav <- Mav1        # 1yr worth of seasonal average (non ts obj)
  Fit <- Fit12       # Fit you are using for forecasting
  
  Y.h  <- predict(Fit, n.ahead=12, newxreg=c(1:12)/frequency(Y)+max(time(Y)) )   # Y can be of any freq
  Yhat <- ts(Mav + cbind(Y.h$pred, Y.h$pred-1.96*Y.h$se, Y.h$pred+1.96*Y.h$se), start=start(Y.h$pred), freq=frequency(Y))  

  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black","red","blue","blue"), main="12-step prediction")
  lines(M.av1+Fit$coef["intercept"]+Fit$coef["time(Ds.co2)"]*time(Ds.co2), col="green")

  #- Zoomed In
  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black","red","blue","blue"),
      xlim=c(2003, 2006), main="12-step prediction with 95PI")
  lines(M.av1+Fit$coef["intercept"]+Fit$coef["time(Ds.co2)"]*time(Ds.co2), col="green")



4. Forecasting CO2 with SARIMA

If above CO2 data was fit with SARIMA, and forecasted.

  acf1 <- acf; library(TSA); acf <- acf1
  data(co2)  #- we are using co2 data in TSA package (there's another one in R)

  library(forecast)
  source("http://gozips.uakron.edu/~nmimoto/477/TS_R-90.txt")  

  plot(co2, type="o", main='CO2 Data')

  ## In Lec-22, after taking diff( , 12). sMA(1) coefficient was very close to 1,
  ## indicating Trend + Seasonality + AR(p) + e model



  #--- Forecast with Model with d=1, D=1 ---

  Fit2 = Arima(co2, order=c(0,1,1), seasonal=list(order=c(0,1,1), period=12))
  Fit2
## Series: co2 
## ARIMA(0,1,1)(0,1,1)[12] 
## 
## Coefficients:
##           ma1     sma1
##       -0.5792  -0.8206
## s.e.   0.0791   0.1137
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.5683:  log likelihood=-139.54
## AIC=285.08   AICc=285.29   BIC=293.41
  #--- 12-step prediction ---
  Y   <- co2      # Y should be TS object
  Fit <- Fit2     # Fit you are using for forecasting
  
  Y.h  <- predict(Fit, n.ahead=12)   # Y.h$pred is TS object
  Yhat <- ts(cbind(Y.h$pred, Y.h$pred-1.96*Y.h$se, Y.h$pred+1.96*Y.h$se), start=start(Y.h$pred), freq=frequency(Y))  
  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black","red","blue","blue"),
      main="12-step prediction with 95PI")
  abline(h=0)
  abline(h=mean(Y), col="blue")

  ts.plot(Y, Yhat, type="o", col=c("black","red","blue","blue"),
      xlim=c(2003, 2006), main="12-step prediction with 95PI")
